rsonal friendships with many of the regime officials. Four Days in Hitler’s Germany is a clearly written and engaging story that addresses how King truly believed that any threat to peace would come only from those individuals who intended to thwart the Nazi agenda, which as King saw it, was concerned primarily with justifiable German territorial and diplomatic readjustments. Mackenzie King was certainly not alone in misreading the omens in the 1930s, but it would be difficult to find a democratic leader who missed the mark by a wider margin. This book seeks to explain the sources and outcomes of King’s misperceptions and diplomatic failures, and follows him as he returns to Germany to tour the appalling aftermath of the very war he had tried to prevent.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh  aCanada.  aHitler.  aMackenzie King.  aNazi Germany.  aSecond World War.  aantisemitism.  acommemoration.  amemory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148750565340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487505653423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487505653.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles